1
00:01:44,375 --> 00:01:47,492
Afternoon, Mr Smith.
Afternoon, Mr Munroe.

2
00:01:57,215 --> 00:01:59,171
- Hello, Bert.
- Hello, Gus.

3
00:01:59,255 --> 00:02:02,088
- Lovely afternoon. Hmph!
- Not 'alf, it ain't.

4
00:02:09,735 --> 00:02:12,533
- Hello, Mr Miggs.
- Hello, young fellow, me lad.
What you got there?

5
00:02:12,615 --> 00:02:14,845
- Package for Major General Denistoun.
- Retired.

6
00:02:14,935 --> 00:02:18,086
Oh. Been chasin' 'im 'alf over
the bloomin' country, that 'as.

7
00:02:18,175 --> 00:02:20,643
- Oh, it has? I'll see that he gets it.
- [Bell Dings]

8
00:02:20,735 --> 00:02:22,646
- Thanks, chum.
- Righto.

9
00:02:26,175 --> 00:02:29,850
Here you are, Horace.
Give that to Major General Denistoun.

10
00:02:29,935 --> 00:02:33,928
And this here, kindly hand it to
Mr Quentin Reynolds. Do you know him?

11
00:02:34,015 --> 00:02:36,210
Yes. [Sniffles]
He's the American.

12
00:02:36,295 --> 00:02:38,126
All right, hop along now.

13
00:02:38,215 --> 00:02:40,524
<i>And blow your</i>
<i>blinkin'nose, will you?</i>

14
00:02:44,255 --> 00:02:46,325
[Sniffles]

15
00:02:53,495 --> 00:02:55,451
- Food is pretty scarce, though.
- Mr Quentin Reynolds?

16
00:02:55,535 --> 00:02:57,412
- Yes.
- Telegram, sir.

17
00:02:58,815 --> 00:03:01,454
- Thank you, son. Excuse me, boys.
- Thank you.

18
00:03:01,535 --> 00:03:03,412
<i>Yes, certainly.</i>

19
00:03:07,415 --> 00:03:09,610
- Beg pardon, sir.
- Yes?

20
00:03:09,695 --> 00:03:11,845
- Package, sir.
- Oh, thank you, Horace.

21
00:04:18,375 --> 00:04:20,843
Well, I'll be damned.
His ears <i>are</i> pierced.

22
00:04:20,935 --> 00:04:22,971
That's what we've been
telling you, old boy.

23
00:04:23,055 --> 00:04:26,730
Yes, but a man like Denistoun.
Old school tie. Sandhurst.

24
00:04:26,815 --> 00:04:30,364
A general with his ears
pierced like a gypsy.

25
00:04:30,455 --> 00:04:33,128
Why, it's fantastic.
What's the idea?

26
00:04:33,215 --> 00:04:34,887
No one has ever had
the cheek to ask him.

27
00:04:34,975 --> 00:04:36,966
He was in Europe
when the war broke out.

28
00:04:37,055 --> 00:04:38,886
Came home
and there they were.

29
00:04:38,975 --> 00:04:41,967
Must have been black magic.
He came home a changed man.

30
00:04:42,055 --> 00:04:44,410
Used to be a most
frightful stuffed shirt.

31
00:04:44,495 --> 00:04:47,055
Quite a nice old chap now.
I say, what's the rush?

32
00:04:47,135 --> 00:04:50,844
Oh, this. I have to grab
a 5.30 plane for Paris.

33
00:04:50,935 --> 00:04:54,564
But look, if either of you boys
get the lowdown on Denistoun's ears...

34
00:04:54,655 --> 00:04:58,045
- drop me a line, will ya?
- Be glad to, if and when.

35
00:04:58,135 --> 00:05:00,091
- Fine.
- Well, so long, Reynolds.

36
00:05:00,175 --> 00:05:02,086
- And thanks for everything.
- So long, man.

37
00:05:02,175 --> 00:05:04,131
I'll be seeing you.

38
00:05:07,295 --> 00:05:09,604
- Nice fellow... for an American.
- Hmm.

39
00:05:09,695 --> 00:05:13,768
Right. Right you are.
Righto.

40
00:05:13,855 --> 00:05:17,450
Bit of a mob on that Paris plane, sir,
but I finally wangled it.

41
00:05:17,535 --> 00:05:19,526
5.30, Northolt. The fog's lifted.

42
00:05:19,615 --> 00:05:21,446
Oh, you're wonderful, Miggs.
You're beautiful!

43
00:05:21,535 --> 00:05:23,924
I love you, Miggs!
Come, let me give you a kiss.

44
00:05:25,735 --> 00:05:28,044
You'd better hurry, sir.
That is, if you're going to pack.

45
00:05:28,135 --> 00:05:29,773
Thank you, Miggs.

46
00:05:45,015 --> 00:05:47,609
- Why don't you ask me and have it over?
- What?

47
00:05:48,895 --> 00:05:50,806
- At least you'll admit you're curious.
- Curious?

48
00:05:50,895 --> 00:05:53,125
- Why, curious about what?
- My ears.

49
00:05:53,215 --> 00:05:55,092
Oh, I'm sorry.
I didn't mean-

50
00:05:55,175 --> 00:05:57,689
Oh, come, come.
Own up.

51
00:05:57,775 --> 00:06:01,450
Well, all right.
But it is odd, you know.

52
00:06:01,535 --> 00:06:05,210
What I mean is, they look
like they've been pierced for earrings.

53
00:06:05,295 --> 00:06:09,288
Do they really?
By Jove, they probably do.

54
00:06:09,375 --> 00:06:11,525
Well, well.

55
00:06:11,615 --> 00:06:15,290
- I was wondering if you'd
mind talking about it.
- Not at all. Not at all.

56
00:06:15,375 --> 00:06:18,367
Then why has it been
top secret for so long?

57
00:06:18,455 --> 00:06:20,685
For the very simple reason
that nobody's ever asked me.

58
00:06:20,775 --> 00:06:23,926
Wait a minute.
Wait a minute.

59
00:06:24,015 --> 00:06:25,846
Let's go back a bit.

60
00:06:25,935 --> 00:06:29,814
How did you know
that I was thinking about your ears?

61
00:06:29,895 --> 00:06:33,968
- How did you know?
- Well, that's part of my story.

62
00:06:34,055 --> 00:06:35,886
There's a woman in it, of course.

63
00:06:35,975 --> 00:06:38,535
A woman of such extraordinary
accomplishments that I-

64
00:06:39,935 --> 00:06:42,768
well, it all started
shortly before war broke out.

65
00:06:42,855 --> 00:06:45,415
I was in Germany. A prisoner.

66
00:06:45,495 --> 00:06:47,451
Before the war? A prisoner?

67
00:06:47,535 --> 00:06:49,412
Yes, I was a lieutenant colonel then.

68
00:06:49,495 --> 00:06:53,613
And together with a youngster
named Byrd was on a special mission.

69
00:06:53,695 --> 00:06:55,651
Very hush-hush, you know.

70
00:06:55,735 --> 00:06:57,851
Not at all in my line, exactly...

71
00:06:57,935 --> 00:07:00,893
except that I spoke
German like a native.

72
00:07:00,975 --> 00:07:03,443
We were trying to nail
a poison gas formula.

73
00:07:03,535 --> 00:07:07,847
Something new. An appalling
by-product of Nazi frightfulness.

74
00:07:07,935 --> 00:07:09,846
Anyway, I don't think
I was very good...

75
00:07:09,935 --> 00:07:13,166
because the blighters knocked us off
like a couple of sitting pheasants.

76
00:07:14,575 --> 00:07:16,964
And we were being held
for questioning, Byrd and I...

77
00:07:17,055 --> 00:07:20,206
in a farmhouse
not very far from Weimar.

78
00:07:20,295 --> 00:07:23,685
<i>[Denistoun] One way and another,</i>
<i>we were in a pretty tight spot.</i>

79
00:07:23,775 --> 00:07:26,687
<i>Our guards, an S.S. First lieutenant</i>
<i>and a couple of troopers...</i>

80
00:07:26,775 --> 00:07:30,290
<i>were as pretty a crew</i>
<i>of cutthroats as ever you saw.</i>

81
00:07:30,375 --> 00:07:33,287
<i>There was also an official</i>
<i>of the Geheime Staatspolizei.</i>

82
00:07:33,375 --> 00:07:37,288
<i>A dreadful fellow named Hoff.</i>
<i>Oh, he was a horror!</i>

83
00:07:37,375 --> 00:07:40,333
<i>He'd questioned us</i>
<i>more than once and we knew.</i>

84
00:07:40,415 --> 00:07:43,851
<i>Young Byrd called him</i>
<i>"Jack the Ripper."</i>

85
00:07:43,935 --> 00:07:47,974
<i>J felt particularly sorry for young Byrd.</i>
<i>Nicest chap imaginable.</i>

86
00:07:48,055 --> 00:07:52,651
<i>His affection for me was positively</i>
<i>touching. A sort of hero worship.</i>

87
00:07:52,735 --> 00:07:55,374
<i>Used to embarrass</i>
<i>the devil out of me.</i>

88
00:07:55,455 --> 00:07:57,605
<i>Though why he liked me</i>
<i>J'll never know.</i>

89
00:07:57,695 --> 00:08:00,812
<i>Looking back, J must have been</i>
<i>a pretty offensive sort of fellow.</i>

90
00:08:00,895 --> 00:08:03,125
<i>You know, pre-war army.</i>
<i>Spit-and-polish.</i>

91
00:08:03,215 --> 00:08:06,412
<i>"Stand to attention when you address</i>
<i>an officer. "All that sort of thing.</i>

92
00:08:06,495 --> 00:08:09,567
<i>Anyhow, we'd planned to escape,</i>
<i>and this was the night.</i>

93
00:08:09,655 --> 00:08:11,566
<i>This was it.</i>

94
00:08:11,655 --> 00:08:14,453
<i>Wasn't much of a plan.</i>
<i>Odds against it coming off...</i>

95
00:08:14,535 --> 00:08:16,924
<i>were about</i>
<i>a thousand to one.</i>

96
00:08:17,015 --> 00:08:18,846
<i>We'd chosen this particular</i>
<i>night to escape...</i>

97
00:08:18,935 --> 00:08:21,403
<i>because Hitler was going</i>
<i>to broadcast from Munich...</i>

98
00:08:21,495 --> 00:08:25,727
<i>and a pretty safe bet his laddie boys</i>
<i>downstairs would listen in.</i>

99
00:08:25,815 --> 00:08:29,251
<i>J didn't know about Byrd,</i>
<i>but personally J was scared stiff.</i>

100
00:08:29,335 --> 00:08:32,884
I don't know about you,
but personally I'm in an absolute sweat.

101
00:08:34,135 --> 00:08:36,012
- Positively trickling, sir.
- <i>[Dog Barking]</i>

102
00:08:36,095 --> 00:08:38,928
<i>## [Triumphal Music On The Radio]</i>

103
00:08:39,015 --> 00:08:40,926
Well, here we go.

104
00:08:41,015 --> 00:08:43,449
- Let's hope only one comes up.
- More than one, we're sunk.

105
00:08:43,535 --> 00:08:47,050
<i>[Hitler, Crowd On Radio]</i>
Sieg heil! Sieg heil!

106
00:08:47,135 --> 00:08:50,889
- Sieg heil!
- Why doesn't somebody throw him a fish?

107
00:08:50,975 --> 00:08:53,205
<i>Sieg heil!</i>

108
00:08:53,295 --> 00:08:56,014
- [Hitler On Radio] <i>Wir mussten-</i>
- [All] Heil Hitler!

109
00:08:56,095 --> 00:08:59,212
<i>... in der minoritaet belieben</i>
<i>wir die wertvollsten...</i>

110
00:08:59,295 --> 00:09:02,526
<i>- elemente des kampfes</i>
<i>und des opfersinns...</i>
<i>- [Dog Barking]</i>

111
00:09:02,615 --> 00:09:05,448
<i>- In der nation mobilisierten die,</i>
<i>die zu allen zeiten nicht...</i>
<i>- [Dog Barking]</i>

112
00:09:05,535 --> 00:09:08,003
- Ah! That dog! Why doesn't somebody-
- <i>shh!</i>

113
00:09:08,095 --> 00:09:09,926
<i>[Hitler]</i>
Die minderheit ausgemacht haben.

114
00:09:10,015 --> 00:09:12,813
Ja. Ja.

115
00:09:12,895 --> 00:09:16,331
- [Crowd Applauding On Radio]
- [Banging]

116
00:09:16,415 --> 00:09:18,451
- Zweig!
- [Banging Stops]

117
00:09:18,535 --> 00:09:20,491
[Hitler]
<i>Weil dieser beste rassenwert-</i>

118
00:09:20,575 --> 00:09:22,406
<i>[Dog Barking]</i>

119
00:09:22,495 --> 00:09:24,850
They're coming, sir.

120
00:09:24,935 --> 00:09:29,486
<i>[Hitler]</i>... mutig und kuehn die
fuehrung des reiches-

121
00:09:29,575 --> 00:09:33,045
Pfeiffer, see what's the matter
with that dog! Pfeiffer!

122
00:09:33,135 --> 00:09:35,524
<i>[Hitler]</i>
...groesserer zahl dieser fuehrung...

123
00:09:35,615 --> 00:09:39,130
angeschlossen und unterstellt.

124
00:09:41,535 --> 00:09:43,765
I say, look!
There's something frightfully wrong!

125
00:09:43,855 --> 00:09:47,052
- <i>J saw him put something</i>
<i>in his mouth. Then he-</i>
- <i>[Zweig] What was it?</i>

126
00:09:47,135 --> 00:09:50,286
- He said it was an aspirin.
- Aspirin! Where would he get aspirin?

127
00:09:50,375 --> 00:09:53,526
And then he had a sort of fit.
His heart's hardly beating!

128
00:09:53,615 --> 00:09:55,685
You're a stupid English swine!

129
00:09:55,775 --> 00:09:57,970
If he's taken poison,
if he's dead, I'll-

130
00:10:00,255 --> 00:10:04,567
<i>[Crowd Cheering,</i>
<i>Applauding On Radio]</i>

131
00:10:13,495 --> 00:10:18,091
<i>[Hitler]</i> Wer sich als traeger seines
besten blutes fuehlt...

132
00:10:18,175 --> 00:10:22,293
und dieses wissen zur fuehrung
der nation erhoben hat...

133
00:10:22,375 --> 00:10:25,447
und entschlossen ist diese
fuehrung zu behalten.

134
00:10:25,535 --> 00:10:30,165
<i>Wahrzunehmen und nicht-</i>
[Crowd Cheering]

135
00:10:31,215 --> 00:10:33,171
Where is Obersturmfuehrer Zweig?

136
00:10:33,255 --> 00:10:35,371
<i>He's upstairs.</i>
<i>He told me to go see about that dog.</i>

137
00:10:35,455 --> 00:10:37,332
You imbecile!
Get back up there!

138
00:10:37,415 --> 00:10:39,212
All right, you blighters!

139
00:10:41,655 --> 00:10:44,089
Take off the uniform.
Tie him up.

140
00:10:45,695 --> 00:10:48,528
I say, old boy.
You can't do that, you know.

141
00:10:48,615 --> 00:10:51,175
[Hitler On Radio]
<i>Von ihnen wird mehr gefordert als von-</i>

142
00:10:51,255 --> 00:10:53,132
- Get on with it, man!
- Sorry.

143
00:10:53,215 --> 00:10:55,604
- Hurry up!
<i>...den millionen der</i>
<i>uebrigen volksgenossen.</i>

144
00:10:58,175 --> 00:11:02,646
<i>[Denistoun] We stole Hoff's car,</i>
<i>a big, black brute of a Mercedes...</i>

145
00:11:02,735 --> 00:11:05,693
<i>and heading for Stuttgart,</i>
<i>drove all night.</i>

146
00:11:05,775 --> 00:11:09,654
<i>One thought cheered us.</i>
<i>They couldn't broadcast a general</i>
<i>alarm for two Englishmen...</i>

147
00:11:09,735 --> 00:11:11,612
<i>without tipping off</i>
<i>the British embassy.</i>

148
00:11:11,695 --> 00:11:14,129
<i>Jt would have to be</i>
<i>a private manhunt.</i>

149
00:11:14,215 --> 00:11:17,446
<i>However, sooner or later,</i>
<i>we knew we'd have to scupper the car.</i>

150
00:11:17,535 --> 00:11:19,491
<i>So shortly after dawn-</i>

151
00:11:33,415 --> 00:11:35,406
- Well, here's where we separate.
- Right, sir.

152
00:11:35,495 --> 00:11:38,248
Now listen carefully. First thing
you must do is get rid of that uniform.

153
00:11:38,335 --> 00:11:40,690
Get some other clothes. You'll probably
have to steal them, understand?

154
00:11:40,775 --> 00:11:43,243
- Perfectly.
- Then make your way to Esbach,
near Freiburg.

155
00:11:43,335 --> 00:11:46,611
<i>Esbach, remember.</i>
<i>And J'll join you there.</i>

156
00:11:46,695 --> 00:11:49,926
Now here's the thing.
Whoever gets to Esbach first...

157
00:11:50,015 --> 00:11:52,483
marks the road signpost
to Freiburg with three dots...

158
00:11:52,575 --> 00:11:54,452
and then waits for the other.
Is that clear?

159
00:11:54,535 --> 00:11:56,890
Quite. Three dots
on the signpost to Freiburg.

160
00:11:56,975 --> 00:11:59,364
Yes. Then we'll carry on
from where we left off.

161
00:11:59,455 --> 00:12:01,923
- Contact Professor Krosigk.
- <i>Yes. How about money?</i>

162
00:12:02,015 --> 00:12:04,006
Loads. Hoff was
absolutely stinking with it.

163
00:12:04,095 --> 00:12:06,165
That's good.
Well, good luck to you.

164
00:12:07,375 --> 00:12:09,331
I say, sir.
Thanks awfully, sir.

165
00:12:09,415 --> 00:12:13,090
- I mean for everything.
You've been absolutely marvellous.
- Goodbye.

166
00:12:18,895 --> 00:12:23,252
Yes, and thanks to Hoff's blunderings,
we've lost a good five hours.

167
00:12:23,335 --> 00:12:26,486
Of course the man
is an idiot. Goodbye.

168
00:12:28,095 --> 00:12:31,053
You are, you know,
with all your brains in your belly.

169
00:12:34,735 --> 00:12:39,206
Hmm. The car was
last seen near Marbach.

170
00:12:39,295 --> 00:12:43,254
If no further reports come in,
I'm going to assume that the car
has been disposed of.

171
00:12:43,335 --> 00:12:48,170
Possibly in a river.
The Neckar, for instance. Come here.

172
00:12:54,015 --> 00:12:56,051
Heavily wooded country.

173
00:12:57,695 --> 00:13:00,812
I think we shall begin from here.

174
00:13:02,095 --> 00:13:03,926
Yes.

175
00:13:43,415 --> 00:13:47,966
<i>## [Woman Humming]</i>

176
00:14:03,255 --> 00:14:07,965
<i>## [Humming Continues]</i>

177
00:14:20,695 --> 00:14:25,211
## [Humming]

178
00:14:34,855 --> 00:14:39,326
## [Humming Continues]

179
00:14:43,535 --> 00:14:46,527
<i>[Woman]</i>
<i>Jn there it is very damp.</i>

180
00:14:46,615 --> 00:14:49,209
<i>J have good fire here.</i>

181
00:14:51,055 --> 00:14:53,933
And stew.
## [Humming]

182
00:14:59,615 --> 00:15:04,245
## [Humming]

183
00:15:14,215 --> 00:15:16,092
- You are hungry.
- Yes.

184
00:15:16,175 --> 00:15:19,724
Yes. As a matter of fact,
I am, very.

185
00:15:19,815 --> 00:15:23,774
I wonder, would you sell me
some of that, whatever it is?

186
00:15:41,895 --> 00:15:44,534
- Sit down.
- Thank you.

187
00:15:44,615 --> 00:15:47,083
Thank you very much.

188
00:15:47,175 --> 00:15:49,643
I make good fish stew.

189
00:15:49,735 --> 00:15:54,013
- <i>Look.</i>
- Yes, it looks excellent.
Onions and potatoes.

190
00:15:54,095 --> 00:15:57,246
And garlic and barley
and mushrooms.

191
00:15:57,335 --> 00:15:59,451
Plenty of fine, fat fish.

192
00:16:06,655 --> 00:16:09,010
The fish I catch in the river.

193
00:16:09,095 --> 00:16:12,974
The vegetables,
tonight was farmer with a sick cow.

194
00:16:13,055 --> 00:16:16,286
I made it well. Oh, it was easy.

195
00:16:16,375 --> 00:16:18,809
This morning I put black curse on it.

196
00:16:20,415 --> 00:16:22,246
[Branches Rustling]

197
00:16:26,695 --> 00:16:28,970
That is Apple.

198
00:16:29,055 --> 00:16:31,569
- Apple?
- <i>My horse.</i>

199
00:16:37,415 --> 00:16:39,883
Stop watching.
There's nobody.

200
00:16:39,975 --> 00:16:42,170
You're safe here.
Quite safe.

201
00:16:47,855 --> 00:16:50,323
You look like a military man.

202
00:16:51,895 --> 00:16:54,011
Eat! It is good.

203
00:16:55,415 --> 00:16:57,371
Thank you.

204
00:17:16,855 --> 00:17:19,369
- There's something on your chin.
- Huh?

205
00:17:19,455 --> 00:17:21,286
There's something
on your chin.

206
00:17:21,375 --> 00:17:25,527
Ah. This is to keep
evil eye away. Good.

207
00:17:26,775 --> 00:17:29,687
Gypsy superstition.

208
00:17:29,775 --> 00:17:33,609
By the way, I thought gypsies
always travelled around in caravans.

209
00:17:35,375 --> 00:17:38,651
You want to know why
I travel alone, huh?

210
00:17:38,735 --> 00:17:42,887
It was that evil,
misbegotten son of a goat, that Zoltan.

211
00:17:42,975 --> 00:17:45,773
May he rot and swell
and split himself inside out.

212
00:17:45,855 --> 00:17:48,813
With coals of fire in his belly
may he die slowly.

213
00:17:50,495 --> 00:17:52,725
Better you put that
coat on, <i>liebling.</i>

214
00:17:52,815 --> 00:17:55,045
Coat?

215
00:17:55,135 --> 00:17:57,524
Thank you, I'm not cold.

216
00:17:57,615 --> 00:17:59,924
I know it is a military coat.

217
00:18:01,335 --> 00:18:05,248
And there's also a good pair
of trousers too. Huh?

218
00:18:07,455 --> 00:18:10,606
And you were going to throw
into the river that bundle.

219
00:18:10,695 --> 00:18:14,813
Tsk, tsk, tsk. You must never throw away
things that are worth good money.

220
00:18:19,615 --> 00:18:22,004
German uniform.

221
00:18:23,615 --> 00:18:26,049
You're not German.

222
00:18:26,135 --> 00:18:30,094
You're... English... huh?

223
00:18:30,175 --> 00:18:33,611
Madame, you're drawing
some very dangerous conclusions.

224
00:18:33,695 --> 00:18:36,607
That man you kill,
you look in his mouth?

225
00:18:36,695 --> 00:18:40,529
You should. Sometimes these Germans
have gold in their teeth.

226
00:18:42,495 --> 00:18:44,963
You are the colonel, huh?

227
00:18:46,815 --> 00:18:49,454
They catch the other one,
your friend?

228
00:18:49,535 --> 00:18:53,813
Oh, <i>liebling, liebling,</i>
you must not kill me. Not with that.

229
00:18:53,895 --> 00:18:57,126
The patrols would hear.
They would come.

230
00:18:57,215 --> 00:19:00,730
Oh, don't be afraid, <i>geliebter.</i>

231
00:19:00,815 --> 00:19:05,411
Before I ever saw you, when the water
spirits told me you were coming...

232
00:19:05,495 --> 00:19:09,283
I say to myself,
"This will be my man."

233
00:19:10,735 --> 00:19:15,331
<i>Liebling,</i> you are my man. Mine.

234
00:19:16,575 --> 00:19:19,806
- Nothing can change that.
- Never mind that nonsense.

235
00:19:19,895 --> 00:19:23,171
How did you find out about me
and the escape and the rest of it?

236
00:19:23,255 --> 00:19:27,294
They know it in the town.
They're searching the forest and the lake.

237
00:19:33,335 --> 00:19:35,246
Good wool.

238
00:19:39,375 --> 00:19:41,252
And gloves.

239
00:19:41,335 --> 00:19:44,293
Oh! Mm!

240
00:19:44,375 --> 00:19:46,411
I never before had gloves.

241
00:19:46,495 --> 00:19:50,249
Hmm.
Beautiful gloves.

242
00:19:53,015 --> 00:19:55,734
- That is right.
- What's right?

243
00:19:55,815 --> 00:19:57,851
What you were thinking.

244
00:19:59,735 --> 00:20:02,203
That it would be safer
to travel with me.

245
00:20:02,295 --> 00:20:05,924
As a matter of fact, I-
how did you know what I was thinking?

246
00:20:07,775 --> 00:20:10,494
- It is there. Yes.
- The wagon?

247
00:20:10,575 --> 00:20:14,568
We could travel by day. Back lanes.

248
00:20:14,655 --> 00:20:18,125
Gypsy lanes.
They are not watched.

249
00:20:21,015 --> 00:20:24,291
How far you think you go
in these German officer's boots, huh?

250
00:20:24,375 --> 00:20:27,014
- I do wish you'd stop reading my mind.
- They always look at your feet.

251
00:20:27,095 --> 00:20:30,485
So frightfully disconcerting.
Like being found without one's trousers.

252
00:20:30,575 --> 00:20:33,009
Oh, <i>mein süßer!</i>

253
00:20:33,095 --> 00:20:34,926
Why do you not trust me?

254
00:20:35,015 --> 00:20:36,892
Afraid I'll have to.
I've no alternative.

255
00:20:36,975 --> 00:20:39,967
Come then, into the wagon.
It is warm.

256
00:20:41,615 --> 00:20:45,290
Good wagon. Not like
others with holes. Come.

257
00:20:45,375 --> 00:20:47,889
- Give me that.
- No. Tomorrow...

258
00:20:47,975 --> 00:20:50,569
in the morning, early,
we get rid of it.

259
00:20:50,655 --> 00:20:53,123
Now you are to sleep. Come.

260
00:21:02,375 --> 00:21:04,809
- You didn't tell me your name.
- Liddie.

261
00:21:04,895 --> 00:21:08,490
"Liddie"? If you don't mind,
I think I'll call you Lydia.

262
00:21:11,175 --> 00:21:13,131
"Lydia"?

263
00:21:13,215 --> 00:21:15,331
Huh. That is nice.

264
00:21:16,695 --> 00:21:18,765
<i>Jojezakad kedvedsen.</i>

265
00:21:20,095 --> 00:21:23,053
Tomorrow, I have
wonderful coat for you.

266
00:21:23,135 --> 00:21:26,093
Fine blue and yellow gypsy coat.

267
00:21:26,175 --> 00:21:28,370
And boots and razor.

268
00:21:29,975 --> 00:21:31,966
Razor belong to
my second husband.

269
00:21:32,055 --> 00:21:36,014
Thank you, I-your husband?
Where is he?

270
00:21:36,095 --> 00:21:40,008
- He kill a <i>gadze</i> and they hang him.
- Good. I mean, poor fellow.

271
00:21:44,615 --> 00:21:46,970
Good, huh? Huh?

272
00:21:48,695 --> 00:21:51,846
Here you sleep.
Come, take off boots.

273
00:21:55,615 --> 00:21:58,288
Lydia, what is a <i>gadze?</i>

274
00:21:59,935 --> 00:22:02,733
Someone who is not gypsy.

275
00:22:02,815 --> 00:22:06,046
[Groaning]
<i>Gadze</i> sounds like a swear word.

276
00:22:06,135 --> 00:22:10,287
It is, but not when he has blue eyes
and brings you luck.

277
00:22:12,015 --> 00:22:15,212
You know, I'm perfectly
capable of undressing, you know?

278
00:22:22,735 --> 00:22:25,124
Oh, this is comfortable.

279
00:22:25,215 --> 00:22:27,126
It's very pleasant, indeed.

280
00:22:28,455 --> 00:22:31,447
By Jove, I'm tired.
I must be getting old.

281
00:22:31,535 --> 00:22:35,767
No! You are young
and you are strong...

282
00:22:35,855 --> 00:22:38,164
and you are my beautiful man.

283
00:22:38,255 --> 00:22:40,485
Please. Please, your hands.

284
00:22:40,575 --> 00:22:43,931
Couldn't you arrange to sit
on them or something?

285
00:22:44,015 --> 00:22:46,051
As a matter of fact,
I'll sleep by the fire.

286
00:22:46,135 --> 00:22:49,525
No. Outside, I must watch.
By the river.

287
00:22:49,615 --> 00:22:53,403
- What for?
- The Nivashi.

288
00:22:53,495 --> 00:22:57,374
- I beg your pardon?
- The Nivashi and the Pavushti.

289
00:22:57,455 --> 00:23:01,209
- The spirits that live in the water.
- Oh, yes, yes, the pixies.

290
00:23:02,655 --> 00:23:04,805
They sent you to me
because I have no man.

291
00:23:04,895 --> 00:23:07,693
- Oh, tommyrot!
- No, truly.

292
00:23:07,775 --> 00:23:10,847
Five days now I travel alone.

293
00:23:12,055 --> 00:23:14,205
Woman should not be alone.

294
00:23:14,295 --> 00:23:17,844
So tonight, when spirits
come out of river...

295
00:23:17,935 --> 00:23:20,813
I will thank them for you.

296
00:23:20,895 --> 00:23:23,125
[Snoring]

297
00:23:32,895 --> 00:23:35,409
What is that ghastly odour?

298
00:23:35,495 --> 00:23:37,611
- My hair.
- Your hair?

299
00:23:37,695 --> 00:23:40,289
Uh-huh. Look.

300
00:23:40,375 --> 00:23:42,491
- Jasmine, violet.
- Mm-hmm. Mm-hmm.

301
00:23:42,575 --> 00:23:45,612
[Sniffing]
And cod liver oil! Oh, my word!

302
00:23:45,695 --> 00:23:50,086
Good, huh? Tomorrow,
on your hair, I put some.

303
00:23:51,335 --> 00:23:54,372
Now you rest, <i>mein süßer.</i>

304
00:24:03,535 --> 00:24:05,526
What the devil!

305
00:24:40,055 --> 00:24:43,730
- Lydia, your husband,
did he have any papers?
- Papers?

306
00:24:43,815 --> 00:24:47,854
Yes, you know, identification card
or whatever I'd need if I took his place...

307
00:24:47,935 --> 00:24:51,325
- in name only.
- No. No papers.

308
00:24:51,415 --> 00:24:54,771
- Huh.
- They take them. But I have his clothes.

309
00:24:55,935 --> 00:24:57,846
Clothes?

310
00:25:03,695 --> 00:25:07,085
Lydia, do you think you
could make me into a gypsy?

311
00:25:09,375 --> 00:25:11,605
What idea!

312
00:25:11,695 --> 00:25:13,970
What cleverness!

313
00:25:14,055 --> 00:25:16,649
Huh! And in a <i>gadze!</i>

314
00:25:16,735 --> 00:25:19,613
<i>Oh,</i> mein süßer!

315
00:25:19,695 --> 00:25:22,414
I can make gypsy
out of log of wood.

316
00:25:22,495 --> 00:25:24,326
Oh...

317
00:25:24,415 --> 00:25:26,724
and you are not
log of wood.

318
00:25:38,375 --> 00:25:43,085
## [Humming]

319
00:25:49,375 --> 00:25:54,051
## [Humming]

320
00:26:01,535 --> 00:26:03,730
<i>## [Humming]</i>

321
00:26:03,815 --> 00:26:07,694
What is that
filthy mumbo-jumbo?

322
00:26:07,775 --> 00:26:10,573
Stain, to make
your white skin gypsy.

323
00:26:11,935 --> 00:26:14,165
<i>And in your ears,</i>
<i>J put holes.</i>

324
00:26:14,255 --> 00:26:15,847
Little holes.

325
00:26:15,935 --> 00:26:18,085
- Holes?
- <i>Yes.</i>

326
00:26:18,175 --> 00:26:21,212
For my husband's
beautiful gold earrings.

327
00:26:23,935 --> 00:26:28,645
When I finish, you will
even smell like gypsy.

328
00:26:28,735 --> 00:26:31,693
Now look here, old girl.
Let's not overdo this.

329
00:26:32,855 --> 00:26:35,449
## [Humming]

330
00:26:35,535 --> 00:26:37,014
- Ow!
- Lay still.

331
00:26:37,095 --> 00:26:39,131
There's no need
to tear off my ears.

332
00:26:39,215 --> 00:26:43,811
## [Humming]

333
00:26:45,935 --> 00:26:49,291
[Groaning]

334
00:26:49,375 --> 00:26:51,843
## [Humming]

335
00:26:51,935 --> 00:26:53,971
Come.

336
00:26:55,415 --> 00:26:58,885
- [Shouts]
- It hurt?

337
00:26:58,975 --> 00:27:03,253
No. No, but I can
still die of tetanus.

338
00:27:03,335 --> 00:27:06,008
Tetanus?
I do not know. Come.

339
00:27:07,895 --> 00:27:12,047
<i>[Denistoun] Lydia, this awful coat!</i>
<i>Why, it's frightening!</i>

340
00:27:12,135 --> 00:27:14,091
Put it on.

341
00:27:14,175 --> 00:27:17,247
<i>- But where on earth did you get it?</i>
- I stole it.

342
00:27:17,335 --> 00:27:20,964
But do not worry.
I steal it from friend. [Spits]

343
00:27:22,295 --> 00:27:24,172
<i>Then you did him a favour.</i>

344
00:27:30,135 --> 00:27:32,091
<i>Well?</i>

345
00:27:36,935 --> 00:27:40,166
Oh, <i>mein süßer!</i>

346
00:27:40,255 --> 00:27:43,247
Oh, <i>mein süßer!</i>

347
00:27:43,335 --> 00:27:45,246
<i>Jaj istenem!</i>

348
00:27:45,335 --> 00:27:48,725
Oh. Oh!
Look at yourself.

349
00:27:48,815 --> 00:27:51,932
Oh. Oh.

350
00:27:55,695 --> 00:27:58,448
- Not bad.
- Bad?

351
00:27:58,535 --> 00:28:02,369
You are wonderful.
You are beautiful!

352
00:28:02,455 --> 00:28:07,370
Mm! You look like wild bull.
Girls will be crazy for you.

353
00:28:07,455 --> 00:28:10,891
But these eyes, they won't fool anybody.
They're blue, you know.

354
00:28:12,055 --> 00:28:15,889
Keep them low.
Look humble. Gypsies do.

355
00:28:15,975 --> 00:28:18,205
<i>Gadzes</i> teach us how.

356
00:28:54,975 --> 00:28:57,011
- What now?
- Hmph.

357
00:28:58,535 --> 00:29:01,368
- Now you push.
- I beg your pardon?

358
00:29:01,455 --> 00:29:03,332
Go, push. Go!

359
00:29:19,335 --> 00:29:21,405
<i>Geliebter.</i>

360
00:29:21,495 --> 00:29:24,214
I just find name for you.

361
00:29:24,295 --> 00:29:26,251
Janos Kalompa.

362
00:29:26,335 --> 00:29:29,611
Janos Ka- oh, great Scott, Lydia.
Can't you do better than that?

363
00:29:29,695 --> 00:29:33,005
- What's the matter
with your husband's name?
- Uh-uh.

364
00:29:33,095 --> 00:29:36,690
Dead man's name.
Bad luck. No.

365
00:29:36,775 --> 00:29:39,733
<i>Janos Kalompa.</i>
<i>Good.</i>

366
00:29:39,815 --> 00:29:43,854
He was young fiddler
in Transylvania.

367
00:29:43,935 --> 00:29:48,884
Oh... how he could
fiddle! [Sighs]

368
00:29:50,015 --> 00:29:51,892
<i>That Janos.</i>

369
00:29:53,095 --> 00:29:56,326
How I loved him. Ha.

370
00:29:56,415 --> 00:29:58,406
Come. Sit here.

371
00:29:58,495 --> 00:30:01,373
- Come.
- I'm perfectly all right here, thank you.

372
00:30:01,455 --> 00:30:04,492
- Oh...
- Now behave, Lydia!

373
00:30:04,575 --> 00:30:06,452
- But I love you.
- Now look here.

374
00:30:06,535 --> 00:30:10,494
We just simply cannot go on having
these attacks of- well, these attacks.

375
00:30:10,575 --> 00:30:13,487
- It's positively indecent.
- Oh, <i>mein süßer.</i>

376
00:30:15,415 --> 00:30:17,246
Now look, get this
clear once and for all.

377
00:30:17,335 --> 00:30:19,451
You simply must learn
to behave like a good woman.

378
00:30:19,535 --> 00:30:22,254
But I am good woman.

379
00:30:22,335 --> 00:30:25,930
I just want to kiss you little.
Come, I show you. You will like.

380
00:30:26,015 --> 00:30:27,926
You jolly well
stay where you are!

381
00:30:29,775 --> 00:30:34,644
If you dare to move as much as an inch,
I'll- I'll thrash you.

382
00:30:34,735 --> 00:30:36,965
Oh...

383
00:30:37,055 --> 00:30:39,728
first you beat me, huh?

384
00:30:39,815 --> 00:30:42,454
And then you'll be sorry.

385
00:30:42,535 --> 00:30:46,323
Then we kiss and make up.
[Chuckles Seductively]

386
00:30:49,495 --> 00:30:51,531
Here, take whip.

387
00:30:54,255 --> 00:30:56,246
Giddap.

388
00:31:47,975 --> 00:31:49,931
<i>[Lydia]</i>
<i>Stop,</i> liebling.

389
00:31:55,055 --> 00:31:57,171
Lydia, stop it.
Don't you know that's stealing?

390
00:31:57,255 --> 00:31:59,644
Yes, stealing.
But I like apples.

391
00:32:00,695 --> 00:32:02,447
Sit down. Come on.

392
00:32:02,535 --> 00:32:04,571
[Denistoun Makes Kissing Sound]

393
00:32:11,855 --> 00:32:16,485
## [Humming]

394
00:32:27,735 --> 00:32:31,125
## [Humming]

395
00:32:31,215 --> 00:32:34,252
<i># Ha te engem #</i>

396
00:32:34,335 --> 00:32:38,010
<i># Szint oly szivvel #</i>

397
00:32:38,095 --> 00:32:41,610
<i># Szeretnel #</i>

398
00:32:41,695 --> 00:32:44,334
<i># Nagyobb lenne #</i>

399
00:32:44,415 --> 00:32:48,966
<i># Melebb lenne #</i>

400
00:32:49,055 --> 00:32:55,290
<i># Szerelmunk a tengernel #</i>

401
00:32:56,575 --> 00:33:00,011
# Ha te engem #

402
00:33:00,095 --> 00:33:04,646
# Szint oly szivvel #

403
00:33:04,735 --> 00:33:07,090
# Szeretnel #

404
00:33:08,175 --> 00:33:11,212
<i># Nagyobb lenne #</i>

405
00:33:11,295 --> 00:33:16,892
<i># Melebb lenne #</i>

406
00:33:16,975 --> 00:33:23,448
<i># Szerelmunk a tengernel ##</i>

407
00:33:28,895 --> 00:33:31,693
Hmm, nice.

408
00:33:31,775 --> 00:33:35,370
Oh, <i>liebling,</i>
if you only knew words.

409
00:33:35,455 --> 00:33:37,332
Mm, such words.

410
00:33:37,415 --> 00:33:41,169
Oh, such love!
Oh, <i>mein süßer!</i>

411
00:33:55,575 --> 00:33:57,406
Uh!

412
00:34:16,775 --> 00:34:19,972
## [Lydia Singing Gypsy Folk Song]

413
00:34:26,935 --> 00:34:28,812
Oh!

414
00:34:28,895 --> 00:34:33,446
## [Singing Continues]

415
00:34:39,135 --> 00:34:42,810
Tell my fortune.
Gypsy, tell my fortune.

416
00:34:42,895 --> 00:34:44,851
I tell fortune. Come.

417
00:34:46,175 --> 00:34:48,131
Now, you have good hand.

418
00:34:48,215 --> 00:34:50,775
See? Line of life is strong.

419
00:34:50,855 --> 00:34:55,053
But you have been in danger of death
three times, huh?

420
00:34:55,135 --> 00:34:59,526
Now I see happy, long life for you.
I see two husbands, huh?

421
00:34:59,615 --> 00:35:02,083
Two? Oh, thank you.

422
00:35:02,175 --> 00:35:04,166
- Giddap! Come on!
- Thank you.

423
00:35:07,775 --> 00:35:12,166
Mama, mama! The gypsy told
me I would have two husbands.

424
00:35:12,255 --> 00:35:15,053
Ah, that's silly.
Don't pay attention.

425
00:35:15,135 --> 00:35:18,730
Hmm. You know, she thought
I was really a gypsy.

426
00:35:18,815 --> 00:35:20,692
It was earrings.

427
00:35:20,775 --> 00:35:25,007
## [Humming]

428
00:35:25,095 --> 00:35:28,883
"You have been in danger
of death three times."

429
00:35:28,975 --> 00:35:31,853
- You ought to be ashamed of yourself.
- Why?

430
00:35:31,935 --> 00:35:34,324
Sometimes it's true.

431
00:35:34,415 --> 00:35:37,373
You know, in England, for this
sort of hocus-pocus, you'd go to jail.

432
00:35:37,455 --> 00:35:40,333
I go here also. Many times.

433
00:35:40,415 --> 00:35:42,371
In winter, not bad.

434
00:35:52,455 --> 00:35:54,332
Tell fortune?

435
00:36:00,575 --> 00:36:02,452
Fortune?

436
00:36:02,535 --> 00:36:05,607
Lydia, please, I must get to Freiburg.
Let's get a move on!

437
00:36:05,695 --> 00:36:08,334
These fools have money.
I get a little.

438
00:36:08,415 --> 00:36:10,246
Is forbidden, but I try.

439
00:36:10,335 --> 00:36:12,291
We don't need any.
I have enough money.

440
00:36:12,375 --> 00:36:14,411
Of money there is never enough.

441
00:36:14,495 --> 00:36:17,532
And also is woman's job
to get money for her man.

442
00:36:23,015 --> 00:36:25,245
- Tell fortune?
- <i>[Denistoun] Come on!</i>

443
00:36:30,695 --> 00:36:32,572
Fortune?
Tell fortune?

444
00:36:35,135 --> 00:36:37,046
Watch this.

445
00:36:38,695 --> 00:36:40,572
Giddap!

446
00:36:45,775 --> 00:36:48,130
You, get down. Get down!

447
00:36:53,575 --> 00:36:55,486
Gypsy, tell my fortune.

448
00:36:57,695 --> 00:36:59,890
Well?

449
00:36:59,975 --> 00:37:04,651
Ah. Ah! Three times
you've been in danger of death.

450
00:37:04,735 --> 00:37:08,330
See? The line of your life
in three places is broken.

451
00:37:08,415 --> 00:37:09,609
