684
00:57:42,855 --> 00:57:44,732
- I come from the signpost!
- Yes?

685
00:57:44,815 --> 00:57:47,283
The dots! The dots! On the
signpost are three more dots.

686
00:57:47,375 --> 00:57:49,809
- Who put them there?
- It was <i>gadze</i> with bicycle.

687
00:57:49,895 --> 00:57:52,568
- You saw him?
- With my own eyes I see him.

688
00:57:54,775 --> 00:57:56,731
[Boy] Be careful!
There's soldiers working in the woods!

689
00:57:56,815 --> 00:57:59,204
<i>Liebling,</i> be careful!
<i>Liebling!</i>

690
00:57:59,295 --> 00:58:01,206
<i>[Sawing]</i>

691
00:58:21,775 --> 00:58:24,653
- Tell your fortune, master?
- No.

692
00:58:24,735 --> 00:58:27,374
- Cross palm with silver.
- Look, will you please run along?

693
00:58:27,455 --> 00:58:31,050
Master, at this moment
you are in great danger.

694
00:58:31,135 --> 00:58:34,411
<i>[Sawing Continues]</i>

695
00:58:39,295 --> 00:58:41,934
Pump up your bloomin'
bike, guv'nah?

696
00:58:42,015 --> 00:58:44,131
- Aye!
- Good heavens!

697
00:58:44,215 --> 00:58:47,605
- By Jove, that's you.
I mean, it is, isn't it?
- Yes, I suppose it is.

698
00:58:47,695 --> 00:58:49,606
Oddly enough,
I sometimes doubt it.

699
00:58:49,695 --> 00:58:52,255
My word, sir, that get-up.
Those earrings.

700
00:58:52,335 --> 00:58:55,532
An absolute knockout, sir.
Really. Who is this?

701
00:58:55,615 --> 00:58:58,573
Oh, yes, I forgot.
Miss Lydia, Mr Byrd.

702
00:58:58,655 --> 00:59:00,964
How do you do?

703
00:59:01,055 --> 00:59:04,491
- Lydia, better go take a look at them.
- I go tell their fortune.

704
00:59:04,575 --> 00:59:08,488
Maybe they tell me
something, huh?

705
00:59:08,575 --> 00:59:10,566
- My word, sir.
- What that woman's done for me.

706
00:59:10,655 --> 00:59:13,123
- Fortune, tell fortune.
- You just wouldn't believe it.

707
00:59:13,215 --> 00:59:15,046
- Let's get on with this blasted bike.
- <i>Fortune!</i>

708
00:59:15,135 --> 00:59:17,330
Standing there, we'll be knocked off
like sitting ducks.

709
00:59:17,415 --> 00:59:21,090
- Awfully glad you made it, son.
- When I saw those three dots of yours...

710
00:59:21,175 --> 00:59:23,973
I went off in the bushes
and did hand-springs, but really.

711
00:59:24,055 --> 00:59:26,011
- And now for your friend, Krosigk, eh?
- Right, sir.

712
00:59:26,095 --> 00:59:28,290
You write a note, give it to me.
I'll take it to him.

713
00:59:28,375 --> 00:59:32,334
You? Oh, no, that won't do at all.
The whole point is Krosigk knows me.

714
00:59:32,415 --> 00:59:35,930
He's one of my father's oldest friends.
He's known me since I was that high.

715
00:59:36,015 --> 00:59:39,166
You'll stay here. Wait at the gypsy camp.
It's down by the river.

716
00:59:39,255 --> 00:59:42,247
- Is that an order, sir?
- Don't be an ass. Of course it isn't.

717
00:59:42,335 --> 00:59:44,803
- I'm just telling you.
- <i>## [Drums Beating]</i>

718
00:59:44,895 --> 00:59:47,284
Don't talk, don't look,
just give me your hand.

719
00:59:51,135 --> 00:59:54,093
Ah, you have very
lucky hand, master.

720
00:59:54,175 --> 00:59:57,884
Rarely have I seen hand
with so much good fortune.

721
00:59:57,975 --> 01:00:02,844
<i>## [Drum Continues]</i>

722
01:00:02,935 --> 01:00:06,245
You see this line?
That is your life. It-

723
01:00:06,335 --> 01:00:10,647
My word, sir, you're a knockout.
An absolute knockout.

724
01:00:11,855 --> 01:00:15,643
Liebling?

725
01:00:15,735 --> 01:00:18,533
<i>Liebling,</i> last night
they came to inn, the gestapo.

726
01:00:18,615 --> 01:00:22,927
<i>One was big, like hog.</i>
<i>They say here, he has scar.</i>

727
01:00:23,015 --> 01:00:26,405
Hoff. Come back.
Come back, I say.

728
01:00:32,095 --> 01:00:34,689
Why your friend
ride away so sudden?

729
01:00:34,775 --> 01:00:36,811
Because he knew I'd-
I'd never let him go.

730
01:00:36,895 --> 01:00:41,127
Lydia, something's happened to me.

731
01:00:41,215 --> 01:00:44,048
It's terrifying, incredible.

732
01:00:44,135 --> 01:00:48,014
- I read his fortune and-
- Yes?

733
01:00:48,095 --> 01:00:51,405
Lydia, that boy's going to die.

734
01:00:51,495 --> 01:00:53,326
I saw it in his hand.

735
01:00:53,415 --> 01:00:56,691
How, I don't know, but there it was.

736
01:00:56,775 --> 01:01:00,006
Lydia, I tell you, he's going to die,
and I let him go.

737
01:01:00,095 --> 01:01:04,247
Do not be sad, <i>liebling.</i>

738
01:01:04,335 --> 01:01:06,974
If you see it, it is true.

739
01:01:07,055 --> 01:01:10,684
<i>There's nothing you can do.</i>

740
01:01:15,535 --> 01:01:18,254
Come, <i>liebling.</i> Come.

741
01:01:29,015 --> 01:01:33,566
## [Humming]

742
01:01:43,375 --> 01:01:48,733
<i># Senkisem #</i>

743
01:01:48,815 --> 01:01:55,163
<i># Borul #</i>

744
01:01:55,255 --> 01:02:00,613
<i># A kopor #</i>

745
01:02:00,695 --> 01:02:07,533
<i># Sojara #</i>

746
01:02:14,215 --> 01:02:20,245
<i># Most latszik meg #</i>

747
01:02:20,335 --> 01:02:26,888
<i># Ki az igazi #</i>

748
01:02:26,975 --> 01:02:30,172
<i># Arva #</i>

749
01:02:30,255 --> 01:02:34,009
## [Humming]

750
01:02:41,295 --> 01:02:45,254
<i>[Lydia] There are no wings</i>
<i>on bicycles,</i> liebling.

751
01:02:45,335 --> 01:02:49,408
<i>And that man,</i>
<i>this Krosigk, where he live...</i>

752
01:02:49,495 --> 01:02:52,453
<i>is good five miles.</i>

753
01:02:52,535 --> 01:02:55,572
Give to your friend time.

754
01:02:55,655 --> 01:02:58,408
Give to him time.

755
01:02:58,495 --> 01:03:01,771
<i>## [Woman Humming]</i>

756
01:03:11,135 --> 01:03:15,731
You know, Lydia,
I used to be a rationalist.

757
01:03:15,815 --> 01:03:18,249
- What is that?
- Well, it's sort of believing...

758
01:03:18,335 --> 01:03:21,372
only in what you see or hear...

759
01:03:21,455 --> 01:03:23,923
or feel.

760
01:03:24,015 --> 01:03:27,371
But lately, I've begun to suspect
there are more things...

761
01:03:27,455 --> 01:03:31,767
in heaven and earth
than I ever dreamed in my philosophy.

762
01:03:32,815 --> 01:03:35,932
You learn much
when you learn that.

763
01:03:40,975 --> 01:03:45,127
You know, you never did
tell my fortune.

764
01:03:49,415 --> 01:03:52,168
You get back
to your country... safe.

765
01:03:52,255 --> 01:03:55,327
You still know
what I'm thinking.

766
01:03:55,415 --> 01:03:59,328
You are easy, <i>liebling...</i>

767
01:03:59,415 --> 01:04:01,883
very easy.

768
01:04:03,535 --> 01:04:05,730
What else?

769
01:04:09,535 --> 01:04:14,290
You will be famous
and you'll never go hungry...

770
01:04:14,375 --> 01:04:17,128
except in your heart.

771
01:04:18,655 --> 01:04:21,010
What else?

772
01:04:22,735 --> 01:04:26,410
You have been in danger
of death three times.

773
01:04:26,495 --> 01:04:30,124
I can go on
from there myself.

774
01:04:33,415 --> 01:04:36,248
You're thinking
I'll be leaving you soon.

775
01:04:38,255 --> 01:04:40,644
How you know?

776
01:04:40,735 --> 01:04:45,729
You're easy, <i>liebling</i>, very easy.

777
01:04:50,935 --> 01:04:55,565
Lydia, afterwards...

778
01:04:55,655 --> 01:04:58,727
I mean, when I'm gone...

779
01:04:58,815 --> 01:05:02,569
would you go back to Zoltan?

780
01:05:02,655 --> 01:05:07,365
- Would that make you unhappy?
- Yes! Yes, it would, very.

781
01:05:07,455 --> 01:05:12,165
Oh! What would Zoltan want
of woman whose heart is stone?

782
01:05:13,815 --> 01:05:18,093
See? Already it is growing cold.

783
01:05:20,895 --> 01:05:23,284
Oh, Lydia.

784
01:05:23,375 --> 01:05:25,969
I want you to know that
in these last few days...

785
01:05:26,055 --> 01:05:28,967
I've been very happy.

786
01:05:29,055 --> 01:05:32,525
Happier than I thought
it possible to be.

787
01:05:32,615 --> 01:05:35,334
And that's very odd because
they've been days...

788
01:05:35,415 --> 01:05:38,725
of danger and uncertainty.

789
01:05:38,815 --> 01:05:43,411
I don't suppose I've begun
to realize it until...

790
01:05:43,495 --> 01:05:47,932
until now that my time
with you is almost run out.

791
01:05:48,015 --> 01:05:50,245
You are the most wonderful
person I ever met.

792
01:05:50,335 --> 01:05:52,895
<i>Your generosity...</i>

793
01:05:52,975 --> 01:05:55,614
<i>and your warmth</i>
<i>and affection...</i>

794
01:05:55,695 --> 01:05:57,686
and your loyalty and devotion.

795
01:05:57,775 --> 01:06:01,973
The way you spill over with it.
It's made me feel very good...

796
01:06:02,055 --> 01:06:04,364
<i>and very secure...</i>

797
01:06:04,455 --> 01:06:08,084
and very inadequate.

798
01:06:12,135 --> 01:06:16,174
Oh, you not know
your sweetness.

799
01:06:16,255 --> 01:06:20,851
You say something.
Maybe it is your head you turn...

800
01:06:20,935 --> 01:06:24,211
<i>and smile at me.</i>

801
01:06:26,295 --> 01:06:31,323
And then there's beauty
in you like water in sun.

802
01:06:31,415 --> 01:06:35,647
And it make my heart
pour down into me...

803
01:06:35,735 --> 01:06:38,886
'til I love you so.

804
01:06:38,975 --> 01:06:41,364
More than I can bear.

805
01:06:43,815 --> 01:06:46,887
Oh, <i>liebling, liebling.</i>

806
01:06:46,975 --> 01:06:50,604
[Crying]

807
01:06:50,695 --> 01:06:53,129
<i>[Machine-gun Fire]</i>

808
01:06:53,215 --> 01:06:55,649
<i>[Machine-gun Fire Continues]</i>

809
01:07:00,415 --> 01:07:02,975
<i>[Jndistinct German]</i>

810
01:07:03,055 --> 01:07:05,853
Byrd? Byrd!

811
01:07:05,935 --> 01:07:07,812
Go in woods quick.
Leave him with me.

812
01:07:07,895 --> 01:07:10,887
Krosigk, never got to him.

813
01:07:10,975 --> 01:07:13,694
- Come on, help me
get him away from here.
- No, no, go away.

814
01:07:13,775 --> 01:07:17,211
Leave me. Find Krosigk. Tell him I-

815
01:07:18,815 --> 01:07:21,010
<i>[Hoff]</i>
<i>Halt!</i>

816
01:07:22,815 --> 01:07:27,127
- There he is!
- Go away, <i>liebling.</i> Go away.

817
01:07:34,695 --> 01:07:37,493
Before he dies
he has got to talk.

818
01:07:37,575 --> 01:07:39,850
Where is Denistoun?

819
01:07:39,935 --> 01:07:43,291
- I told you I wanted him alive.
- I shot for the legs.

820
01:07:43,375 --> 01:07:47,527
<i>Rindvieh!</i>
I think he's coming to.

821
01:07:47,615 --> 01:07:52,166
Where is Denistoun?
Where is the colonel?

822
01:07:52,255 --> 01:07:55,804
Get his shirt off.
I will make him talk.

823
01:07:55,895 --> 01:07:57,931
<i>[Ripping]</i>

824
01:08:08,455 --> 01:08:12,243
<i>[Hoff]</i>
<i>Where is Denistoun? Where is he?</i>

825
01:08:12,335 --> 01:08:14,803
- <i>Talk!</i>
- No! No!

826
01:08:14,895 --> 01:08:18,126
- <i>[Hoff] Where is the colonel?</i>
- Right here!

827
01:08:19,335 --> 01:08:21,212
Denistoun.

828
01:08:24,095 --> 01:08:27,292
<i>[Gunshots]</i>

829
01:08:40,255 --> 01:08:43,486
Dicky? Dicky,
it's me, Denistoun.

830
01:08:56,975 --> 01:09:00,854
It's no use to grieve.
This is way it has to be.

831
01:09:08,895 --> 01:09:12,365
- Zoltan, get these away from camp.
- Uh-huh.

832
01:09:12,455 --> 01:09:14,685
- Car too?
- Yes.

833
01:09:14,775 --> 01:09:18,654
Bury this boy here in the woods
and all of you get out of here.

834
01:09:18,735 --> 01:09:21,613
You go to Krosigk, huh?

835
01:09:21,695 --> 01:09:24,255
<i>No! No! They catch you!</i>
<i>They kill you!</i>

836
01:09:24,335 --> 01:09:26,849
Go back to your people.
This isn't your war.

837
01:09:26,935 --> 01:09:28,812
- Go on!
- <i>Liebling.</i>

838
01:09:35,775 --> 01:09:37,731
So I asked myself...

839
01:09:37,815 --> 01:09:40,932
why was Byrd seen in
the vicinity of Freiburg?

840
01:09:41,015 --> 01:09:43,848
Not once, mind you,
but three times.

841
01:09:43,935 --> 01:09:46,085
Why is he hanging about?

842
01:09:46,175 --> 01:09:48,643
- For whom is he waiting?
- <i>For the other Englishman.</i>

843
01:09:48,735 --> 01:09:51,203
- Denistoun.
- Of course, but why?

844
01:09:51,295 --> 01:09:53,286
Why meet here?
Why meet at all?

845
01:09:53,375 --> 01:09:57,493
In their shoes, I'd be getting out
of the country as fast as I could.

846
01:09:57,575 --> 01:10:00,612
No, they have business here.

847
01:10:00,695 --> 01:10:04,210
Business important enough
for them to risk their necks.

848
01:10:04,295 --> 01:10:08,527
But what kind of business?
And with whom?

849
01:10:08,615 --> 01:10:11,687
With whom, gentlemen?

850
01:10:11,775 --> 01:10:14,687
<i>Hmm?</i>

851
01:10:18,855 --> 01:10:21,449
What would you say
to our great humanitarian...

852
01:10:21,535 --> 01:10:24,413
that earnest disciple
of brotherly love...

853
01:10:24,495 --> 01:10:28,329
the inventor of
our new poison gas?

854
01:10:28,415 --> 01:10:31,487
What would you say, my friends...

855
01:10:31,575 --> 01:10:34,487
to professor Otto Krosigk?

856
01:10:35,695 --> 01:10:38,209
Yes, Herr Reimann.

857
01:10:38,295 --> 01:10:41,332
Oh, of course you can
come over. Not at all.

858
01:10:41,415 --> 01:10:45,852
We shall be delighted.
Well then. Goodbye, Herr Reimann.

859
01:10:49,055 --> 01:10:52,445
- What does Reimann want?
- He's coming over.

860
01:10:52,535 --> 01:10:55,447
I'm worried, Otto.
He suspects you.

861
01:10:55,535 --> 01:10:57,651
- We're being watched.
- Now, come, my darling.

862
01:10:57,735 --> 01:11:00,374
There's nothing
extraordinary in that.

863
01:11:00,455 --> 01:11:05,529
Today in Germany, everybody is watched,
even the watchers. Come.

864
01:11:05,615 --> 01:11:09,005
Tonight would you be entertaining
the chief of police...

865
01:11:09,095 --> 01:11:13,327
these Nazi party officials
and elite guard officers...

866
01:11:13,415 --> 01:11:15,929
if you weren't forced to?

867
01:11:16,015 --> 01:11:18,734
- They suspect, Otto.
- Let them.

868
01:11:18,815 --> 01:11:23,013
And if they searched me,
would they ever suspect this, uh...

869
01:11:23,095 --> 01:11:25,563
piece of money?

870
01:11:25,655 --> 01:11:27,805
- Let me keep it.
- No, darling, I have got to have it handy.

871
01:11:27,895 --> 01:11:31,365
I never know when and where
I may meet... Byrd.

872
01:11:31,455 --> 01:11:35,687
And if Byrd doesn't show up?

873
01:11:35,775 --> 01:11:39,529
If they have caught him
and sent someone in his place to trap you?

874
01:11:39,615 --> 01:11:42,812
They won't trap me.
If anyone else but Byrd comes...

875
01:11:42,895 --> 01:11:44,806
I won't have anything
to do with him.

876
01:11:44,895 --> 01:11:47,614
Please, stop worrying, will you? Come.

877
01:11:47,695 --> 01:11:51,404
Let's go back to our guests.

878
01:11:53,215 --> 01:11:56,571
<i>[Rumbling]</i>

879
01:11:56,655 --> 01:11:59,215
What are you two doing here?
I told you to get away.

880
01:11:59,295 --> 01:12:01,604
- This man, you see him?
- No, too many people. Now go back.

881
01:12:01,695 --> 01:12:03,845
Go back? Liddie say go in.

882
01:12:03,935 --> 01:12:06,847
Go in, go back?
What is this talk, huh?

883
01:12:06,935 --> 01:12:09,813
We go in and tell fortune.
Then you talk to Krosigk. Easy, huh?

884
01:12:09,895 --> 01:12:12,170
No, go back.
Zoltan, it's not safe for you here.

885
01:12:12,255 --> 01:12:16,089
Already not safe for me there.
Liddie break my head.

886
01:12:16,175 --> 01:12:18,450
Whoa. Whoa.

887
01:12:18,535 --> 01:12:21,174
Go on in, brother.
We waste good time.

888
01:12:21,255 --> 01:12:23,530
Come.

889
01:12:36,255 --> 01:12:40,294
Masters, ladies? Read your fortunes?
Read your palms?

890
01:12:40,375 --> 01:12:42,570
Tell past, present, future.

891
01:12:42,655 --> 01:12:46,091
- Beautiful lady, with your permission-
- You! Be off!

892
01:12:46,175 --> 01:12:49,008
- All of you, get out of here.
- Wait, Herr Lieutenant.

893
01:12:49,095 --> 01:12:52,610
- This may be very amusing.
- Nonsense!

894
01:12:52,695 --> 01:12:55,368
These filthy gypsies.
These non-aryan swine.

895
01:12:55,455 --> 01:12:57,844
We of the master race
should not contaminate ourselves.

896
01:12:57,935 --> 01:13:01,052
Our little policeman,
chewing up the landscape.

897
01:13:01,135 --> 01:13:04,571
Handsome soldier,
like me tell your fortune, huh?

898
01:13:04,655 --> 01:13:07,533
<i>[Major]</i>
<i>Jf you can make it interesting.</i>

899
01:13:07,615 --> 01:13:11,893
- With man like you, easy.
- Is it all right, Krosigk?

900
01:13:11,975 --> 01:13:15,729
- <i>[Krosigk] Of course, by all means.</i>
- This I must hear.

901
01:13:15,815 --> 01:13:18,249
<i>[Man] Ask her if there's</i>
<i>going to be another war.</i>

902
01:13:18,335 --> 01:13:21,293
- Tell your fortune, master,
past, present or future.
- No, gypsy.

903
01:13:21,375 --> 01:13:23,206
I'm not interested. Maybe you?

904
01:13:23,295 --> 01:13:26,446
Not interested in an old Oxford friend,
Herr Krosigk?

905
01:13:26,535 --> 01:13:30,608
- Or his son, Richard Byrd?
- Careful, it's a trick.

906
01:13:32,175 --> 01:13:34,370
Go away.

907
01:13:38,255 --> 01:13:41,327
- <i>Get out of here, gypsy.</i>
- I'm not a gypsy.

908
01:13:41,415 --> 01:13:45,203
- My name is Denistoun. I'm an Englishman.
- Isn't that interesting?

909
01:13:45,295 --> 01:13:48,287
- An English gypsy.
- I told you I'm not a gypsy.
You've got to believe that.

910
01:13:48,375 --> 01:13:50,605
<i>J'm Colonel Denistoun</i>
<i>of the British army.</i>

911
01:13:50,695 --> 01:13:54,085
A colonel with holes in
his ears and rings in them.

912
01:13:54,175 --> 01:13:57,884
<i>That's a little hard for me to swallow.</i>
<i>But frankly, my good man...</i>

913
01:13:57,975 --> 01:14:01,411
I'm not at all interested in
who you are or what you are.

914
01:14:01,495 --> 01:14:04,771
<i>[Mrs Krosigk] Certainly not,</i>
<i>and we don't want our fortunes told.</i>

915
01:14:04,855 --> 01:14:08,973
- We must go back to our guests, Otto.
- Wait! Richard Byrd is dead.

916
01:14:09,055 --> 01:14:11,774
<i>They shot him, tortured him.</i>

917
01:14:11,855 --> 01:14:14,005
He was on his way here
to see you.

918
01:14:15,775 --> 01:14:19,006
Why do you...
tell me all this?

919
01:14:19,095 --> 01:14:22,167
- There... there must be some mistake.
- There's no mistake.

920
01:14:22,255 --> 01:14:24,246
I killed the two brutes
that murdered him.

921
01:14:24,335 --> 01:14:26,849
He counted on you,
you because you're a patriot of humanity...

922
01:14:26,935 --> 01:14:28,812
rather than a tool
of these war-mad Nazis.

923
01:14:28,895 --> 01:14:32,649
That is dangerous talk, gypsy.

924
01:14:32,735 --> 01:14:35,727
Look, there's going to be a war.
A war, do you hear?

925
01:14:35,815 --> 01:14:39,888
Give me your horrible formula
and Germany dare not use it.
You know that <i>we</i> won't!

926
01:14:42,095 --> 01:14:44,848
<i>Jt's your duty as a scientist,</i>
<i>as a humanitarian.</i>

927
01:14:47,855 --> 01:14:50,210
Do I get it?

928
01:14:54,135 --> 01:14:56,888
I don't know what
you are talking about.

929
01:14:56,975 --> 01:14:59,284
<i>[Radio]</i>
Bekanntmachung des oberkommandos.

930
01:14:59,375 --> 01:15:02,447
If ever I get out of this mess,
if I get back to England...

931
01:15:02,535 --> 01:15:04,890
I shall have to tell your friends,
young Byrd's mother and father...

932
01:15:04,975 --> 01:15:08,331
just how their son died. I don't want
to tell them he died for nothing.

933
01:15:08,415 --> 01:15:10,883
<i>[Man]</i>
<i>War! Jt's war!</i>

934
01:15:10,975 --> 01:15:14,172
- War!
- <i>[Jndistinct Chatter]</i>

935
01:15:14,255 --> 01:15:16,974
- Did you hear that, Otto?
- Yes, my dear, I did, I did.

936
01:15:17,055 --> 01:15:20,604
<i>This gypsy's a traitor.</i>
<i>He'll get you into trouble.</i>

937
01:15:20,695 --> 01:15:22,970
No, my dear. No, he won't.

938
01:15:23,055 --> 01:15:26,092
I'll report him to Reimann
when he comes.

939
01:15:26,175 --> 01:15:28,769
I know you think
I'm trying to trick you-

940
01:15:28,855 --> 01:15:32,006
It's war, Herr Krosigk! On the radio,
it just came over! Poland attacked us!

941
01:15:32,095 --> 01:15:34,973
We are already across the Polish border!
<i>Heil Hitler!</i>

942
01:15:35,055 --> 01:15:37,250
<i>Heil Hitler!</i>
<i>Heil Hitler!</i>

943
01:15:37,335 --> 01:15:40,372
- Heil Hitler!
- Deutschland ueber alles!

944
01:15:40,455 --> 01:15:42,923
<i>Hurrah!</i>
<i>Hurrah! Hurrah!</i>

945
01:15:43,015 --> 01:15:46,291
Sieg heil!
Sieg heil!

946
01:15:46,375 --> 01:15:48,570
<i># Deutschland ueber alles #</i>

947
01:15:48,655 --> 01:15:51,169
# Ueber alles in der welt #

948
01:15:51,255 --> 01:15:53,815
- You have it?
- No. Get out I'm in trouble.

949
01:15:53,895 --> 01:15:57,126
- Our luck goes bad.
- Already around neck I feel rope.

950
01:15:57,215 --> 01:16:00,685
You two get away and I'll-
too late.

951
01:16:00,775 --> 01:16:02,652
# Bruederlich zusammenhaelt- #

952
01:16:02,735 --> 01:16:06,330
Good evening.

953
01:16:06,415 --> 01:16:10,090
- I see everyone has heard
the glorious news.
- <i>Yes! Yes! Glorious!</i>

954
01:16:10,175 --> 01:16:12,245
<i>On the radio,</i> heil.

955
01:16:18,335 --> 01:16:21,611
- Good evening, Herr Reimann.
- A little slow getting over, Krosigk.

956
01:16:21,695 --> 01:16:24,129
Had to wait for a report
on two of my men.

957
01:16:24,215 --> 01:16:27,207
They were murdered while
tracking down two enemies of the Reich.

958
01:16:27,295 --> 01:16:29,570
Our enemies are all around us,
Herr Reimann.

959
01:16:29,655 --> 01:16:32,727
Sometimes under our very noses.

960
01:16:32,815 --> 01:16:36,490
How true. As a matter of fact,
I am very glad you came over.

961
01:16:36,575 --> 01:16:39,692
- I just-
- The murderers of my men
were two Englishmen...

962
01:16:39,775 --> 01:16:41,766
named Byrd and Denistoun.

963
01:16:41,855 --> 01:16:45,325
<i>The names mean anything to you?</i>

964
01:16:45,415 --> 01:16:49,010
To me?

965
01:16:49,095 --> 01:16:51,689
I don't understand.

966
01:16:51,775 --> 01:16:55,768
I once knew a Mr Byrd
at Oxford, yes.

967
01:16:55,855 --> 01:17:00,167
- <i>But he is very old now.</i>
- <i>[Reimann] Oh, you admit that?</i>

968
01:17:00,255 --> 01:17:04,168
Do you realize the borders are very
closely guarded now that war is declared?

969
01:17:04,255 --> 01:17:06,610
These men most certainly
will be caught...

970
01:17:06,695 --> 01:17:10,529
- and made to talk!
- Talk about what?

971
01:17:10,615 --> 01:17:15,643
Who are they? Herr Reimann,
that sounds very melodramatic.

972
01:17:15,735 --> 01:17:18,408
Krosigk, we have reason to suspect...

973
01:17:18,495 --> 01:17:21,328
that they may have
some business with you.

974
01:17:21,415 --> 01:17:25,124
Really?

975
01:17:25,215 --> 01:17:28,730
Then I insist that you
post a guard around this house.

976
01:17:28,815 --> 01:17:32,490
I must be protected at all times.

977
01:17:32,575 --> 01:17:35,612
<i>You're very clever, Krosigk, but-</i>

978
01:17:47,335 --> 01:17:50,168
They have been telling
our fortunes...

979
01:17:50,255 --> 01:17:52,644
and very well too.

980
01:17:55,855 --> 01:17:58,449
Get them out of here.

981
01:18:01,775 --> 01:18:04,653
<i>[Krosigk]</i>
<i>Gypsy! Wait.</i>

982
01:18:08,095 --> 01:18:11,451
With your kind permission.

983
01:18:14,055 --> 01:18:17,525
Here. This is what you wanted...

984
01:18:17,615 --> 01:18:20,083
for telling my fortune.

985
01:18:20,175 --> 01:18:22,769
And I believe it too.

986
01:18:22,855 --> 01:18:26,530
<i>Every word of it.</i>

987
01:18:43,095 --> 01:18:45,370
[Whispering]
Let's get away.

988
01:19:01,895 --> 01:19:04,284
Well, this is it.
From here on I travel alone.

989
01:19:04,375 --> 01:19:06,684
What about you and your people?
This war's gonna make it difficult.

990
01:19:06,775 --> 01:19:11,291
We separate, scatter.
Like water in sand.

991
01:19:11,375 --> 01:19:15,368
- Country will swallow us.
- Brother, you've been a good friend.
I shall never forget it.

992
01:19:15,455 --> 01:19:17,446
Farewell, brother.

993
01:19:17,535 --> 01:19:20,652
And one day you take
earrings from ears...

994
01:19:20,735 --> 01:19:25,047
but you find roots of them
in your heart.

995
01:19:26,095 --> 01:19:28,655
Goodbye, Lydia.
Goodbye, my dear.

996
01:19:28,735 --> 01:19:31,693
I go with you to Rhine.
Without me, you do not get out of country.

997
01:19:31,775 --> 01:19:34,005
- No, absolutely no.
- I am your luck.

998
01:19:34,095 --> 01:19:37,485
- I won't have it.
- Ah, brother, with her,
what good is words?

999
01:19:37,575 --> 01:19:40,135
'Til your tongue hang out, you say "no."

1000
01:19:40,215 --> 01:19:44,493
In the end is "yes."
That I have found out. Now go!

1001
01:19:44,575 --> 01:19:47,965
Come, <i>liebling.</i> We must be in mountains
before sun come up. Come.

1002
01:20:57,135 --> 01:20:59,649
<i>[Car Approaching]</i>

1003
01:21:31,255 --> 01:21:33,291
Not much of a war going on.

1004
01:21:33,375 --> 01:21:36,014
Sentries pretty well under cover.

1005
01:21:36,095 --> 01:21:40,293
- Not safe to swim across.
- Lydia, you're not going to try it.

1006
01:21:40,375 --> 01:21:44,004
No, <i>liebling,</i> before I meet you...

1007
01:21:44,095 --> 01:21:46,450
I seldom wash.

1008
01:21:46,535 --> 01:21:50,210
No time learn to swim.

1009
01:21:50,295 --> 01:21:53,412
Let's find a place
to wait until nightfall.

1010
01:22:06,655 --> 01:22:09,453
- I imagine this runs into the Rhine.
- Yes.

1011
01:22:09,535 --> 01:22:11,890
I'll follow the stream
down to the river.

1012
01:22:11,975 --> 01:22:14,125
It's luckier when you stick
close to running water.

1013
01:22:14,215 --> 01:22:16,888
Besides, the sound
will cover my footsteps.

1014
01:22:47,855 --> 01:22:51,052
Oh, <i>liebling.</i>

1015
01:22:51,135 --> 01:22:55,014
There is spell on me.

1016
01:22:55,095 --> 01:22:59,566
My head go round and round...

1017
01:22:59,655 --> 01:23:02,727
and I feel weak...

1018
01:23:02,815 --> 01:23:05,409
and frightened.

1019
01:23:07,175 --> 01:23:11,373
To me nothing matter any more...

1020
01:23:11,455 --> 01:23:14,333
only you.

1021
01:23:16,015 --> 01:23:19,849
All my life I believe
if I do not love one man...

1022
01:23:19,935 --> 01:23:23,974
I love another.

1023
01:23:24,055 --> 01:23:27,127
But now is different.

1024
01:23:27,215 --> 01:23:31,174
Is like... like...

1025
01:23:31,255 --> 01:23:34,133
having sickness.

1026
01:23:34,215 --> 01:23:39,369
No. You never knew
what real love was.

1027
01:23:39,455 --> 01:23:42,652
And I never knew what life was.

1028
01:23:42,735 --> 01:23:45,727
Now we've become like each other.

1029
01:23:45,815 --> 01:23:48,648
We've merged into each other.

1030
01:23:48,735 --> 01:23:53,650
Gypsy, <i>gadze. Gadze,</i> gypsy.

1031
01:23:53,735 --> 01:23:56,568
It's all one, Lydia.

1032
01:24:25,015 --> 01:24:28,485
<i>- Mein süßer.</i>
- Uh-huh.

1033
01:24:28,575 --> 01:24:31,612
Now it is dark.

1034
01:24:36,175 --> 01:24:40,134
No moon, no stars.

1035
01:24:40,215 --> 01:24:42,888
Clouds.

1036
01:24:42,975 --> 01:24:45,967
I told you my luck
would keep you safe, huh?

1037
01:24:51,335 --> 01:24:55,692
- You worry when you swim,
keep money dry, huh?
- Yes.

1038
01:24:55,775 --> 01:25:00,087
Here. Here. Put in here.

1039
01:25:03,455 --> 01:25:07,334
Now you make your way to Switzerland.
You'll be safe there.

1040
01:25:07,415 --> 01:25:11,966
- You too?
- No, the Swiss would intern me.

1041
01:25:14,055 --> 01:25:16,774
But you would be safe.

1042
01:25:16,855 --> 01:25:20,404
No, I can't.

1043
01:25:33,015 --> 01:25:36,974
You... you are only half <i>gadze.</i>

1044
01:25:37,055 --> 01:25:40,730
And I, half gypsy.

1045
01:25:40,815 --> 01:25:43,534
Because I say go.

1046
01:26:08,735 --> 01:26:11,454
Goodbye, Lydia.

1047
01:27:12,615 --> 01:27:15,254
O spirits
of the earth and water...

1048
01:27:15,335 --> 01:27:17,929
guide my beloved.

1049
01:27:18,015 --> 01:27:21,246
Make him strong
like the oak tree.

1050
01:27:21,335 --> 01:27:26,045
Let him live in the beauty
and vigour of his seed.

1051
01:27:27,095 --> 01:27:31,532
Sweet spirits
of the earth and water...

1052
01:27:31,615 --> 01:27:34,334
I give you back my beloved.

1053
01:27:40,735 --> 01:27:43,727
[Spit, Spit, Spit]

1054
01:28:20,255 --> 01:28:23,565
- Paris.
- She was quite a woman.

1055
01:28:23,655 --> 01:28:26,727
Quite, Mr Reynolds, quite.

1056
01:28:26,815 --> 01:28:29,488
- But I thought you said
you returned them to her.
- Did I say that?

1057
01:28:29,575 --> 01:28:31,770
<i>[Woman] We will land in four minutes.</i>
<i>Fasten your safety belts please.</i>

1058
01:28:31,855 --> 01:28:36,087
<i>We will land in four minutes.</i>
<i>Fasten your safety belts please.</i>

1059
01:29:27,415 --> 01:29:30,964
[Spit, Spit, Spit]

1060
01:29:36,735 --> 01:29:38,612
Lydia.

1061
01:29:41,855 --> 01:29:44,653
Oh! Oh.

1062
01:29:44,735 --> 01:29:47,295
Oh, <i>mein süßer!</i>

1063
01:29:47,375 --> 01:29:50,412
Oh! <i>Mein süßer!</i>

1064
01:29:50,495 --> 01:29:54,249
I think you never come.
Oh, I just leaving.

1065
01:29:54,335 --> 01:29:56,485
Oh, <i>mein süßer!</i>

1066
01:29:56,575 --> 01:29:59,567
Oh. Oh. Oh.

1067
01:30:01,335 --> 01:30:03,895
Oh, <i>süßer.</i>

1068
01:30:16,895 --> 01:30:19,489
Come on, Apple. Giddap.

